metadata.name: Tilemoji #237
metadata.description:
This collection of low resolution generative art is presented using emojis rather than an image, so it can be copied like normal text. You are also welcome to take a screenshot for sharing or printing. Most results are designed to fit in a 280 character tweet, except for rare extra large variants. There are five different generative algorithms possible, each with their own set of parameters. Emojis are rendered using the Twemoji font and may look different in some environments.

Thank you for supporting my work during the first year of fxhash. For me it has been a life changing experience. I am forever grateful for all of the art and friendships we've created. Many of us have met on social media, so I developed this special project with a fun way to display and share. Congrats to artists, collectors, and developers for an amazing year!

This work is part of the fxhash anniversary event (#fxhashturnsone)
All of primary sale proceeds will go to Save Pakistan

Code and Outputs are Copyright 2022 Frank Force
Artwork is released under CC BY-NC 4.0 (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0)

metadata.name: Composition #3 Patchwork Quilt #240
metadata.description:
Abstract, non-square(!) composition based on textural strokes and noise. There are a lot of possible combinations with all of the features! 50% chance of two different palette sets. 50% chance to have a brush textured background, and a 50% chance of it being horizontal or vertical. The quadtree rectangles are based on poisson disc sampling based on a simplex noise field. 90% of the compositions will be smaller boxes, and 10% will be large. For each box, there is a 10% chance that it will be oriented opposite of the rest.

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot.

metadata.name: Charcoal Landscapes #22
metadata.description:
This work is an exploration of abstract landscapes using lines that are bounded to 8 directions. This limitation still allows for somewhat organic visuals and creates a visual language more akin to traditional drawing techniques.

Using a vector field with a noise function at different scales, I construct paths starting at random positions and moving to the neighbours cells pointed at by the vector field. Paths have a limitation of length and are bounded to the grid. I create tens of thousands of paths then render progressively on screen.

There are 10 parameters variations and 4 colors, 2 being rare and one very rare.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2021

metadata.name: Temporality #127
metadata.description:
temporality
/ˌtɛmpəˈralɪti/
The state of existing within or having some relationship with time.

Inspired by the patterns and textures formed where land meets water. Swirling river banks, sedimentary plains, estuaries and deltas - sometimes formed in minutes or hours, other times over hundreds of years.

Temporality explores the ideas of impermanence and erosion and the inevitability of change.

As Philip K. Dick writes in A Scanner Darkly:

"Everything in life is just for a while"

Read the accompanying fxtext article for more details on how this collection came about.

= = = = = = = = =

Press [1] to display @ 1400 x 2100 (default)
Press [2] to display @ 4200 x 6300
Press [S] to download the current resolution

p5.js + chroma.js + GLSL
Best viewed in a Chromium browser on a laptop/desktop.

Tested on Chrome/Brave on Android mobile.

metadata.name: Remains #201
metadata.description:
This series explores the remnants and imprints of past events; the unintended consequences and marks left behind: The floor of a painter's studio, layered with splatters and spills; the face of a rock, sculpted by the relentless touch of water and ice; the rusty hood of a forsaken car, weathered and chipped under the harsh sun.

The art piece is crafted by an algorithm simulating the effects of abrasion from a consistent yet dynamic process. It links a thousand pairs of points, harmoniously shifting across the canvas, with delicate lines. At each intersection of these lines, color is applied. To produce the final piece, multiple layers of varying colors and intensities are superimposed.

------

Controls:

- [x] Save a PNG

- [1] Set height to 768
- [2] Set height to 1152 
- [3] Set height to 1536 (default)
- [4] Set height to 2304
- [5] Set height to 3072* 
- [6] Set height to 6144*
- [7] Set height to 9216*
- [8] Set height to 11520*

URL parameters:

- &height={HEIGHT} explicitly sets the render height


* images with height over 3000 pixels render without animating, downloads a PNG automatically after rendering

Please note that high resolution outputs will take several minutes or even longer to render. Highest resolutions have only been successfully tested with Safari on a Mac. If you would like to have assistance in creating high resolution outputs, please contact the author.

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #158
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden “template” canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‘template’ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution
